DataElement.preferredName: Aerodigestive Tract Cancer First Diagnosis Age Range Code
DataElement.preferredDefinition: The code used to represent the age range of the participant when they were first diagnosed with aerodigestive cancer.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: Information pertaining to the first investigation, analysis and recognition of the presence and nature of disease of the anatomic structures forming the upper respiratory tract and upper part of the digestive tract.  They include the oral cavity, sinonasal tract, pharynx, pyriform sinus, larynx, trachea, and esophagus.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: Anatomic structures forming the upper respiratory tract and upper part of the digestive tract.  They include the oral cavity, sinonasal tract, pharynx, pyriform sinus, larynx, trachea, and esophagus.:A tumor composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues.  Malignant neoplasms usually metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision.  The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas (adenocarcinomas or squamous cell carcinomas), Hodgkin's and non-Hodgkin's lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas. -- 2004

Concepts.definition: Anatomic structures forming the upper respiratory tract and upper part of the digestive tract. They include the oral cavity, sinonasal tract, pharynx, pyriform sinus, larynx, trachea, and esophagus.

A neoplasm composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues. Malignant neoplasms often metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision. The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas, Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas.
